What it is:
Consumer Checkpoint is a regular publication from Bank of America Institute that aims to provide a holistic and real-time estimate of US consumers’ spending and their financial well-being. 
Methodology highlights:
The data covers aggregated credit/debit card spending per household from active US households only, including only consumer cardholders making at least five transactions per month, with corporate cards excluded. 
Merchants are identified and classified by Merchant Categorization Code (MCC), then mapped using proprietary methods to the North American Industry Classification System (NAICS) — the same system the Census Bureau uses — to  classify spending by subsector.
Income segmentation is done by splitting households into terciles (lower/middle/higher) based on quantitative income estimates, with thresholds that adjust over time for wage inflation and other factors. 
They also layer in deposit account data (checking/savings balances), after-tax wage and salary growth, credit card delinquency rates, and BNPL adoption — all from BofA’s internal anonymized data.
Where to access it:
	∙	Main landing page: institute.bankofamerica.com/consumer-checkpoint.html
	∙	Monthly PDF reports are published there (e.g., the May 2025 and December 2025 editions)
Important caveat for your use case: The underlying granular data is not publicly downloadable — the reports provide aggregated charts and YoY/MoM metrics. BofA notes that additional information about the methodology used to aggregate the data is available upon request.  So if you need the raw series for a Data Commerce or alternative data play, you’d need to engage BofA Institute directly.
